# The College of Justice and the Supreme Courts of Scotland

## The College of Justice

The College of Justice ([Scottish Gaelic](/Scottish_Gaelic_language): Colaiste a' Cheartais) includes the Supreme Courts of Scotland, and its associated bodies. The constituent bodies of the national [supreme courts](/Supreme_court) are the [Court of Session](/Court_of_Session), the [High Court of Justiciary](/High_Court_of_Justiciary), the [Office of the Accountant of Court](/Office_of_the_Accountant_of_Court), and the Auditor of the Court of Session. &#91;2&#93; &#91;3&#93; &#91;4&#93; Its associated bodies are the [Faculty of Advocates](/Faculty_of_Advocates), the [Society of Writers to His Majesty's Signet](/Society_of_Writers_to_His_Majesty%27s_Signet) and the [Society of Solicitors in the Supreme Courts of Scotland](/Society_of_Solicitors_in_the_Supreme_Courts_of_Scotland).

The College is headed by the [Lord President of the Court of Session](/Lord_President_of_the_Court_of_Session), who also holds the title of Lord Justice General in relation to the [High Court of Justiciary](/High_Court_of_Justiciary), and judges of the Court of Session and High Court are titled [Senators of the College of Justice](/Senators_of_the_College_of_Justice).

### History

The college was founded in 1532 by [King James V](/James_V_of_Scotland) following a [bull](/Papal_bull) issued by [Pope Clement VII](/Pope_Clement_VII) on 15 September 1531. It provided for 10,000 [gold ducats](/Gold_ducat) to be contributed by the [Scottish bishoprics](/Christianity_in_Medieval_Scotland) and [monastic institutions](/Abbeys_and_priories_in_Scotland) for the maintenance of its members, one half of whom would be members of the "ecclesiastical dignity". &#91;5&#93;

The [Parliament of Scotland](/Parliament_of_Scotland) passed the College of Justice Act 1532 (c. 2) on 17 May 1532 authorising the creation of the college with 14 members, half spiritual, half temporal, plus a president and the [Lord Chancellor](/Lord_Chancellor_of_Scotland). The college convened for the first time on 27 May 1532, in the royal presence. Supplementing the 14 ordinary lords, who were called senators, were an indefinite number of supernumerary judges called [extraordinary lords](/Extraordinary_Lord_of_Session).

The founding members of the College of Justice were:

- The Lord Chancellor, [Gavin Dunbar](/Gavin_Dunbar_(Archbishop_of_Glasgow)), [Archbishop of Glasgow](/Archbishop_of_Glasgow)
- The Lord President, Alexander Myln, Abbot of [Cambuskenneth](/Cambuskenneth_Abbey)
- Richard Bothwell, Rector of [Ashkirk](/Ashkirk)
- John Dingwall, Provost of [Trinity College](/Trinity_College_Kirk)
- Henry White, Rector of [Finevin](/Finevin)
- William Gibson, Dean of [Restalrig](/Restalrig)
- Thomas Hay, Dean of [Dunbar](/Dunbar)
- Robert Reid, Abbot of [Kinloss](/Kinloss_Abbey)
- George Ker, Provost of [Dunglass](/Dunglass)
- [Sir William Scott](/William_Scott,_Lord_Balwearie) of Balweary
- [Henry Lauder, Lord St Germains](/Henry_Lauder,_Lord_St_Germains), [King's Advocate](/Lord_Advocate) &#91;6&#93;
- [John Campbell of Lundy](/John_Campbell_of_Lundy)
- [Sir James Colville](/Sir_James_Colville) of [Easter Wemyss](/Easter_Wemyss)
- Sir [Adam Otterburn](/Adam_Otterburn) of [Auldhame](/Auldhame) and Redhall, King's [Advocate](/His_Majesty%27s_Advocate)
- Nicholas Crawford of Oxengangs
- [Francis Bothwell](/Francis_Bothwell) of [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh) (brother of Richard)
- James Lawson of Edinburgh
- Sir James Foulis of [Colinton](/Colinton), who was added at the first meeting of the court when the king made him a "Lord of the Session".

The college at its foundation dealt with underdeveloped [civil law](/Scots_civil_law). It did not dispense justice in criminal matters as that was an area of the law reserved to the king's justice, through the [justiciars](/Justiciar) (hence the High Court of the Justiciary), the [Barony Courts](/Barony_Court) and the [Commission of Justiciary](/Commission_of_Justiciary). The High Court of Justiciary was only incorporated into the College of Justice in 1672. Initially, there was little legal literature. [Acts](/Act_of_the_Parliament_of_Scotland) of the [Parliament of Scotland](/Parliament_of_Scotland) and the books of the Old Law as well as [Roman Law](/Roman_Law) and [canon law](/Canon_law) texts were about all to which the pursuer and defender could refer. It was only after the establishment of the court that this situation improved, with judges noting their decisions in books of practicks.

The [Treaty of Union 1707](/Treaty_of_Union_1707) with [England](/England) preserved the [Scottish Legal System](/Scottish_Legal_System). Article XIX provided "that the Court of Session or College of Justice do after the Union and notwithstanding thereof remain in all time coming within Scotland, and that the Court of Justiciary do also after the Union ... remain in all time coming."

## Supreme Courts of Scotland

### Court of Session

The [Court of Session](/Court_of_Session) is the highest national court of [Scotland](/Scotland) in relation to [civil](/Civil_law_(common_law)) cases. The court was established in 1532 to take on the judicial functions of the royal council. Its jurisdiction overlapped with other royal, state and church courts but as those were disbanded, the role of the Court of Session ascended. The [Acts of Union](/Acts_of_Union_1707) establishing the United Kingdom provided that the court will "remain in all time coming". Cases at [first instance](/Trial_court) are heard in the [Outer House](/Outer_House) by a single judge. The [Inner House](/Inner_House) hears appeals from the Outer House and all other courts and tribunals in Scotland. Only Scottish advocates and solicitor-advocates may argue cases before the court. The Court of Session has sat at [Parliament House](/Parliament_House,_Edinburgh) since 1707. &#91;7&#93; The [Scottish Courts and Tribunals Service](/Scottish_Courts_and_Tribunals_Service) and the [Principal Clerk](/Principal_Clerk_of_Session_and_Justiciary) administers the court and judges.

The creation of the court was part of wider efforts to improve and reform access to justice in Scottish society. By 1153, the local feudal courts had been established. Depending on the part of Scotland where the cause originated, justice might also be available from the local baron or lord of regality, sitting with the king's authority. &#91;8&#93; Parties often found these courts ineffectual. Appeal of the decisions of local courts lay to the king and the Lords of Council, sitting together as the King's Council, or the Parliament of Scotland. The burden on these bodies of hearing appeals led to a growing effort to divest their judicial functions.

### High Court of Justiciary

The [High Court of Justiciary](/High_Court_of_Justiciary) is the [supreme](/Supreme_Courts_of_Scotland) [criminal court](/Scottish_criminal_law) in [Scotland](/Scotland). The High Court is both a [trial court](/Court_of_first_instance) and a [court of appeal](/Court_of_appeal). As a trial court, the High Court sits on circuit at [Parliament House](/Parliament_House,_Edinburgh) or in the adjacent former Sheriff Court building in the [Old Town](/Old_Town,_Edinburgh) in [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh), or in dedicated buildings in [Glasgow](/Glasgow) and [Aberdeen](/Aberdeen). The High Court sometimes sits in various smaller towns in Scotland, where it uses the local [sheriff court](/Sheriff_Court) building. As an appeal court, the High Court sits only in Edinburgh. On one occasion the High Court of Justiciary sat outside Scotland, at [Zeist](/Zeist) in the [Netherlands](/Netherlands) during the [Pan Am Flight 103 bombing trial](/Pan_Am_Flight_103_bombing_trial), as the [Scottish Court in the Netherlands](/Scottish_Court_in_the_Netherlands). At Zeist the High Court sat both as a trial court, and an appeal court for the initial appeal by [Abdelbaset al-Megrahi](/Abdelbaset_al-Megrahi). The High Court will hear appeals from the [sheriff courts](/Sheriff_court) of Scotland where the trial was under [solemn proceedings](/Solemn_proceedings); the High Court will also hear referrals on [points of law](/Point_of_law) from the [Sheriff Appeal Court](/Sheriff_Appeal_Court), and from [summary proceedings](/Summary_offence) in the sheriff courts and [justice of the peace courts](/Justice_of_the_peace_court). Cases can be remitted to the High Court by the [sheriff courts](/Sheriff_court) after [conviction](/Conviction) for [sentencing](/Sentence_(law)), where a sheriff believes that their sentencing powers are inadequate. The High Court can impose a [life sentence](/Life_sentence) but the sheriff has a limit of five years sentencing; both can issue an unlimited [fine](/Fine_(penalty)).

The origins of the High Court derive from the [Justiciar](/Justiciar) and College of Justice, as well as from the medieval [royal courts](/Noble_court) and [barony courts](/Barony_court). The medieval [Justiciar](/Justiciar) (royal judge) took its name from the justices who originally travelled around Scotland hearing cases on circuit or 'ayre'. From 1524, the Justiciar or a depute was required to have a "permanent base" in Edinburgh. &#91;9&#93;

The [King of Scots](/List_of_Scottish_monarchs) sometimes sat in judgment of cases in the early King's Court, and it appears that appeals could be taken from the King's Court to the [Parliament of Scotland](/Parliament_of_Scotland) in civil cases but not in criminal ones. In 1532 the College of Justice was founded, separating [civil](/Civil_law_(common_law)) and [criminal](/Criminal_law) jurisdiction between two distinct courts. The King's Court was, however, normally the responsibility of the Justiciar. The Justiciar normally appointed several deputes to assist in the administration of justice, and to preside in his absence. A legally qualified [clerk](/Clerk_of_court) advised the Justiciar and his deputes as they were generally [noblemen](/Peerage_of_Scotland) and often not [legally qualified](/Legal_education). This clerk prepared all the [indictments](/Indictment) and was keeper of the records. Eventually the influence of the clerk increased until the clerk gained both a vote in the court, and a seat on the [bench](/Bench_(law)) as the [Justice-Clerk](/Lord_Justice_Clerk). &#91;9&#93; &#91;10&#93;

### Office of the Accountant of Court

The [Office of the Accountant of Court](/Office_of_the_Accountant_of_Court) is a public body which is a constituent part of the [Supreme Courts](/Supreme_Courts_of_Scotland) of [Scotland](/Scotland). &#91;11&#93; The Accountant of Court is administered by the [Scottish Courts and Tribunals Service](/Scottish_Courts_and_Tribunals_Service). The Accountant of Court's Office formerly dealt with guardianship cases in respect of adults with [incapacity](/Capacity_(law)). However, following the introduction of the [Adults with Incapacity (Scotland) Act 2000](/Adults_with_Incapacity_(Scotland)_Act_2000) by the [Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament), these cases were transferred to the new [Office of the Public Guardian (Scotland)](/Office_of_the_Public_Guardian_(Scotland)). Based in [Falkirk](/Falkirk), the office of Accountant of Court , also known as the Accountant of the Court of Session (see [Court of Session](/Court_of_Session)), was established by the Judicial Factors Act 1849, and their role was further defined by the Children (Scotland) Act 1995.

The Accountant of Court is responsible for ensuring that those appointed by the Courts as Judicial Factor in terms of the Judicial Factors Act 1849 &#91;12&#93; manage the estates in their charge properly. The Accountant of Court will generally superintend the actions of a Judicial Factor and provide them with the necessary guidance and direction required progress a case. In addition the Accountant of Court is also responsible for investigating any concerns or complaints that are raised against a Judicial Factor. &#91;13&#93;

The Accountant of Court is also responsible for supervising Enforcement Administrators appointed by the Courts to recover assets confiscated in terms of the Proceeds of Crime (Scotland) Act 1995.

### Senators

The [Senators of the College of Justice](/Senators_of_the_College_of_Justice) are judges of the College of Justice, with three types different types of senator – Lords of Session (judges of the Court of Session); Lords Commissioners of Justiciary (judges of the [High Court of Justiciary](/High_Court_of_Justiciary)); and the Chairman of the [Scottish Land Court](/Scottish_Land_Court). Whilst the High Court and Court of Session historically maintained separate judiciary, these are now identical, and the term senator is almost exclusively used in referring to the judges of these courts. On occasions, temporary judges may be appointed to sit in the Supreme Courts of Scotland in order to carry out the same work as permanent senators but will carry out their duties on a part-time basis, and as a result, are referred to as "Judge" rather than Lord or Lady. &#91;14&#93;

The Court of Session has in place "special provisions" allowing it to deal with commercial actions which would ensure that specialist judges handle cases quickly and flexibly. &#91;14&#93; The current commercial judges are [Lord Tyre](/Colin_Tyre,_Lord_Tyre), [Lord Clark](/Alistair_Clark,_Lord_Clark), [Lord Braid](/Peter_Braid,_Lord_Braid) and [Lord Ericht](/Andrew_Stewart,_Lord_Ericht). &#91;14&#93;

